# Git Conventions

## Branch Naming

- Format: `<type>/<short-description>`
- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `ci`
- Use kebab-case for the description
- Keep it short and descriptive

Examples:
- `feat/add-user-auth`
- `fix/login-redirect`
- `chore/update-deps`
- `docs/api-reference`
- `refactor/extract-auth-middleware`

## Conventional Commits

- Format: `<type>(<optional-scope>): <description>`
- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `chore`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `ci`
- Subject line: imperative mood, lowercase, no period, max 72 characters
- Body (optional): explain **why** not what, wrapped at 72 characters
- Footer (optional): `BREAKING CHANGE:`, issue references like `Closes #123`

Examples:
```
feat(auth): add OAuth2 login flow
```
```
fix(api): handle null response from payments service

The payments service returns null when no payment methods exist
instead of an empty array. This caused a TypeError in the
account settings page.

Closes #456
```
```
chore: upgrade turborepo to v2.5
```

## Atomic Commits

Each commit should represent a single logical change. When staged or unstaged changes span multiple concerns, automatically split them into separate commits — do not ask.

How to identify separate concerns:
- Different purpose (e.g., refactor vs. new feature)
- Different scope (e.g., backend vs. frontend, config vs. code)
- Migration/cleanup vs. new functionality
- Dependency updates vs. code changes

When splitting, commit in logical order: foundational changes first (refactors, migrations, config), then new functionality on top.

## PR Description

- **Title**: follows conventional commit format
- **Body** uses this structure:
  - `## Summary` — 1-3 bullet points explaining what and why
  - `## Changes` — list of notable changes
  - `## Test Plan` — how to verify the changes work
  - `## Checklist` — checkboxes for quality gates (tests, lint, build, self-review, docs)
  - `## Before Merge` — any remaining items or conditions that must be met before merging
  
